post_cb({"10359702": {"ViewCount": "35392", "Body": "<p>What's the difference between <code>ios::ate</code> and <code>ios:app</code> when writing to a file.<br>\nIn my view, <code>ios::app</code> gives you the ability to move around in the file, whereas with <code>ios::ate</code> it can only read/write at the end of the file. Is this correct?</br></p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "10359727", "Title": "C++ Filehandling: Difference between ios:app and ios:ate?", "CreationDate": "2012-04-28T01:12:05.987", "Id": "10359702", "CommentCount": "0", "FavoriteCount": "8", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2016-07-19T12:57:06.260", "LastEditorUserId": "514235", "LastActivityDate": "2016-07-19T12:57:06.260", "Score": "39", "OwnerUserId": "823859", "Tags": "<c++><file><fstream><c++-standard-library>", "AnswerCount": "4"}, "10359723": {"Id": "10359723", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>They are specified as follows (in 27.5.3.1.4 of C++11):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_10359702_10359723_0\"><code>app</code> seek to end before each write</p>\n<p id=\"so_10359702_10359723_1\"><code>ate</code> open and seek to end immediately after opening</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>With <code>ios::app</code> the write position in the file is \"sticky\" -- all writes are at the end, no matter where you seek.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-04-28T01:16:30.367", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2012-04-28T01:16:30.367", "ParentId": "10359702", "Score": "28", "OwnerUserId": "13005"}, "10359727": {"Id": "10359727", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It\u2019s the other way around. When <code>ios::ate</code> is set, the initial position will be the end of the file, but you are free to seek thereafter. When <code>ios::app</code> is set, <em>all</em> output operations are performed at the end of the file. Since all writes are implicitly preceded by seeks, there is no way to write elsewhere.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-04-28T01:17:05.710", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2012-04-28T01:17:05.710", "ParentId": "10359702", "Score": "53", "OwnerUserId": "246886"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_10359702_10359723_0": {"length": 6, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 1948}, "so_10359702_10359723_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 1948}}, "n3337": {"so_10359702_10359723_0": {"length": 6, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 1937}, "so_10359702_10359723_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 1937}}, "n4659": {"so_10359702_10359723_0": {"length": 6, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 2219}, "so_10359702_10359723_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 2219}}}, "10359750": {"Id": "10359750", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It is pretty good documented <a href=\"http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/iostream/fstream/open/\">here</a>.</p>\n<p><code>ios::ate</code> \"sets the stream's position indicator to the end of the stream on opening.\"</p>\n<p><code>ios:app</code> \"set the stream's position indicator to the end of the stream before each output operation.\"</p>\n<p>This means the difference that <code>ios::ate</code> puts your position to the end of the file when you open it. <code>ios::app</code> instead puts it at the end of the file every time you flush your stream. If for example you two programs that write to the same log file <code>ios:ate</code> will override anything that was added to the file by the other program since your program opened it. <code>ios:app</code> will instead jump to the end of file each time your programm adds a log entry.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "991425", "LastActivityDate": "2016-03-13T13:41:01.453", "Score": "18", "CreationDate": "2012-04-28T01:21:08.503", "ParentId": "10359702", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "991425", "LastEditDate": "2016-03-13T13:41:01.453"}, "18956716": {"Id": "18956716", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<h2>App:</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_10359702_18956716_0\"><strong>we cannot move the pointer.It will be only at end</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2>Ate:</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_10359702_18956716_1\"><strong>we can move the record pointer to any other place</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-23T10:14:17.610", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-09-23T10:14:17.610", "ParentId": "10359702", "Score": "5", "OwnerUserId": "2806774"}});